===Etymology===
From {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|apologia}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|ἀπολογία|tr=apologia|sc=polytonic||a speech in defense}}, from {{term|ἀπολογοῦμαι|sc=polytonic|tr=apologoumai||I speak in one's defense}}, from {{term|ἀπόλογος|sc=polytonic|tr=apologos||an account, story}}, from {{term|ἀπό|sc=polytonic|tr=apo||from, off}} (see ''[[apo-]]'') + {{term|λόγος|tr=logos|sc=polytonic||speech}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈpɒl.ə.dʒɪ/}}
* {{audio|en-us-apology.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|apologies}}

# An expression of [[remorse]] or [[regret]] for having said or done something that [[harm]]ed another: an instance of [[apologize|apologizing]] (saying that one is [[sorry]]).
#: ''What he said really hurt my feelings, but his '''apology''' sounded so sincere that I couldn't help but forgive him.''
#: ''The CEO made a public '''apology''' for the scandal, and promised full cooperation with the authorities.''
# A formal [[justification]], [[defence]].
#: ''The Apology of Socrates.''

